vior of the banks was deeply conditioned by bankers’ racial views and prejudices. Drawing deeply on a broad range of sources, Hudson reveals that the banks’ experimental practices and projects in the Caribbean often led to embarrassing failure, and, eventually, literal erasure from the archives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBanks and bankingzCaribbean AreaxHistoryy20th century. 0aBanks and bankingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aBranch bankszCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aCapitalismzUnited States. 0aImperialismxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aRacismxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aCaribbean.  aWall Street.  abanking.  acorruption.  acrisis.  adebt.  aimperialism.  ainternational finance.  aregulation.  asovereignty.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226459257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226459257/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles